landcoversFieldNotes: This area definitely has some potential mosquito breeding habitats. There are two houses and some apartments, so there are some flower pots outside. One house (although you cannot tell in the picture) has a large, deep flower bed on the side of it. There are bushes in it, and it is deep enough that water can collect below them. There is also a ditch running along the south side, which fills with water whenever it rains. I saw a coffee cup lid on the ground that had filled with water, there was a broken pipe that could fill with water, there was an old grill as well as a dumpster that could fill with water, and a path made of cinderblocks that can collect water.

This area is constantly wet- moss all over the rocks, ground, and trees is evidence of that. Even the more open, well-lit area outside of the trail has moss growing on its rocks and trees, and even some fungi and mushrooms. Fungi, moss, & lichens bloom on the trees. There are a lot of logs and dead trees that water can collect in. It's so dark that grass doesn't really grow- it's just mud and dead leaves. I placed some mosquito traps here and will be checking them next week. This area has A LOT of mosquitoes, and many other insects and birds as well.

landcoversFieldNotes: I am standing on a path in the Judson Nature Trails. The protected trails run through a beautiful forest filled with diverse plant life; open to the public but tucked away from the rest of the city. A Boy Scout Eagle Project has been maintaing the land, creating benches, and identifying some of the plant life. The trees here are remarkably tall; many of them are over 150 to 200 years old. The deciduous Cedar Elm trees here gave this area its name: Olmos Park. Elms are called "Olmos" in Spanish. Other plant life here includes: semi-evergreen Plateau Live Oak/Live Oak trees, evergreen Guayacan shrubs, evergreen Texas Mountain Laurels, deciduous Lotebush shrubs, deciduous Texas Redbud trees, semi-evergreen Texas Persimmon trees/shrubs, evergreen Texas Palm/Texas Palmetto trees, deciduous American Elm trees, deciduous wild Mustang Grapes, and various vine species. The creek running through here is constantly flooding during heavy rains, making some areas of the forest extremely difficult to maintain. The creek can be seen in the East & South photos, but it is all dried up.
